Quality of life after operations in the abdominal and retroperitoneal cavities: the influence of the abdominal wall anatomic-functional insufficiency. 120 patients with abdominal wall anatomic-functional insufficiency were examined and treated. All patients were divided in 2 similar groups 60 patients each. Patients of the first group had traditional laparotomy wound closure, whereas patients of the second group overcame polypropylene mesh implantation. 21.6% of patients from the first group revealed postoperative ventral hernias at follow-up, none of the second group faced such a problem. Physical component of the quality of live was 3.2 times, and psychological component - 2,6 times higher in patients of the second group.